<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Fannie and Freddie</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the 2008 f=
inancial crisis, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the giant mortgage companies, =
blew up. These were strange companies: They were publicly traded corporatio=
ns owned by shareholders, but they were called =E2=80=9Cgovernment-sponsore=
d enterprises=E2=80=9D (or =E2=80=9CGSEs=E2=80=9D) and had somewhat nebulou=
s government backing. When they blew up, the U.S. government stepped in to =
bail them out with vast piles of money. The bailout agreements were structu=
red to give the government an 80% stake in the enterprises,[1] plus preferr=
ed stock for the money it put in. The government would get a 10% dividend o=
n the preferred stock. Also Fannie and Freddie were put into conservatorshi=
p and effectively run by the Federal Housing Finance Agency, their=C2=A0reg=
ulator.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the years after the bailou=
t, Fannie and Freddie made so little money that they could not regularly pa=
y those dividends, so the government kept putting in more money to keep the=
m solvent. In 2012, Fannie and Freddie agreed with the government =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0represented by the U.S. Department of the Treasury and the FHFA=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0to amend the bailout agreement so that, instead of paying 10=
% a year on the billions of dollars that the government had put into them, =
Fannie and Freddie would just pay the government=C2=A0<em>all of their prof=
its forever</em>. (This was called the =E2=80=9Cthird amendment.=E2=80=9D) =
Over the previous four years, this would have meant a lower payment, becaus=
e Fannie and Freddie were not making enough money to pay that 10% dividend.=
 After the third amendment, though, a weird thing happened and Fannie and F=
reddie started making a lot of money, which they paid over to the Treasury.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nine years later, things are much the same=
. Fannie and Freddie are nominally public companies, but in conservatorship=
 and run by the FHFA. They have shareholders; their stocks trade over the c=
ounter (tickers FNMA and FMCC, respectively); their equity market capitaliz=
ations as of yesterday=E2=80=99s close were $12.9 billion and $7.2 billion,=
 respectively.[2] They are no longer paying all of their income to the Trea=
sury; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24240248.258=
390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWFya2V0d2F0Y2guY29tL3N0b3J5L2Zhbm5pZS1tYWUtZnJlZGRpZS1=
tYWMtY2FuLWtlZXAtZnV0dXJlLWVhcm5pbmdzLXBlci1hZ3JlZW1lbnQtYmV0d2Vlbi10cmVhc3=
VyeS1hbmQtcmVndWxhdG9ycy0yMDIxLTAxLTE0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8f9ec666" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">subsequent =
amendments</a> have allowed them to retain=C2=A0earnings to meet <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuaG91c2luZ3dpcmUuY29tL2FydGljbGVzL2ZoZmEtaXNzdWVzLWZpbmFsLWNhcGl0YWwtcnV=
sZS1mb3ItZmFubmllLW1hZS1mcmVkZGllLW1hYy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf67ed5c0"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">capital r=
equirements</a>. Still they are very much economically owned by the Treasur=
y; they can=E2=80=99t pay dividends to their ordinary shareholders, only bu=
ild capital and pay anything extra to the Treasury. Everyone agrees that th=
is is a weird status quo and that Fannie and Freddie should be returned to =
private hands, but everyone has agreed on that for about a decade now and i=
t has=C2=A0never happened. Maybe one day it will, but I <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDctMTYvc29tZXRpbWVzLWFuYWx5c3Rz=
LWhhdmUtZ29vZC1pZGVhcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb4083e4" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> keep confidently predictin=
g</a> that it won=E2=80=99t happen soon, and I keep being right.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fannie and Freddie=E2=80=99s shareholders are very up=
set about this situation. In particular, they are very upset about the thir=
d amendment. If the third amendment had not happened =E2=80=94=C2=A0if Fann=
ie and Freddie had not agreed with Treasury and the FHFA to replace the gov=
ernment=E2=80=99s 10% dividend with an =E2=80=9Call of our profits=E2=80=9D=
 dividend =E2=80=94=C2=A0then Fannie and Freddie would have been able to ke=
ep their profits over the last nine years; they=E2=80=99d have more capital=
 now and perhaps be able to pay money out to shareholders. Certainly the pu=
blicly traded shares would be worth more. And while technically Fannie and =
Freddie agreed to the amendment, Fannie and Freddie were in conservatorship=
, so basically the FHFA could tell them what to agree to; the third amendme=
nt was not exactly an arm=E2=80=99s-length market transaction.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the shareholders have sued a lot, in various courts=
, arguing that there were various irregularities in the third amendment. Th=
ey have mostly lost. We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMTQtMDItMTkvcGVvcGxlLXJlYWxseS1kaWRuLXQtbGlrZS1mYW5uaWUtbWFlLWF=
uZC1mcmVkZGllLW1hYw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe4838a9c" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about</a> these cases =
from time to time.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One argument that the sh=
areholders had was that the FHFA is unconstitutional. This has been a bit o=
f a cottage industry in recent conservative lawyering, arguing that various=
 regulatory agencies are unconstitutional under the <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVka=
WEub3JnL3dpa2kvQXBwb2ludG1lbnRzX0NsYXVzZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa460bb81=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Appointm=
ents Clause</a>, the bit of the U.S. Constitution that governs how the pres=
ident can appoint executive officers. Basically Congress will set up a regu=
latory agency=C2=A0with a complicated statute providing for=C2=A0how its he=
ad can be hired or fired or supervised, and the agency will go around regul=
ating, and someone won=E2=80=99t like a regulation and will sue saying that=
 the statute is unconstitutional because it doesn=E2=80=99t give the presid=
ent the correct power to hire or fire the head of the agency, so the whole =
agency is void and no one has to follow its regulations.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">The shareholders tried that here with the FHFA, and it went a=
ll the way to the Supreme Court,=C2=A0and today they =E2=80=A6 I guess they=
=C2=A0won a little bit? Not very much. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lm=
dvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yMHBkZi8xOS00MjJfazUzNy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7158=
ba53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Supr=
eme Court ruled today</a> that the FHFA is in fact unconstitutional =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0or a little bit unconstitutional =E2=80=94=C2=A0because the statut=
e authorizing the FHFA only allows its director to be removed =E2=80=9Cfor =
cause,=E2=80=9D while the Constitution requires that the president be able =
to remove the director for any reason or no reason.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But what do you do with that conclusion? It=E2=80=99s not li=
ke the third amendment was adopted by an FHFA director whom the president w=
anted to remove but couldn=E2=80=99t; in fact, it was adopted by an FHFA <e=
m>acting</em> director who was removable=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>cause. =
And it's not like the only thing the FHFA ever did was adopt the third amen=
dment and extract profits from Fannie and Freddie; among other things, it=
=E2=80=99s been running them in conservatorship for the last 13 years. It w=
ould be weird to say that the FHFA is unconstitutional so it has to give Fa=
nnie and Freddie=E2=80=99s profits back to the shareholders, but=C2=A0<em>e=
verything else=C2=A0</em>that happened at Fannie and Freddie over the last =
13 years =E2=80=94=C2=A0every business decision that the FHFA supervised, e=
very profitable trade that the GSEs did in conservatorship, every infusion =
of money from the government, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0was fine.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">So the Supreme Court basically said, meh, it=E2=80=99s a l=
ittle bit unconstitutional, but probably not worth worrying about. But it s=
ent the case back to an appeals court to double-check that conclusion (cita=
tion omitted):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Suppose, for exa=
mple, that the President had attempted to remove a Director but was prevent=
ed from doing so by a lower court decision holding that he did not have =E2=
=80=9Ccause=E2=80=9D for removal. Or suppose that the President had made a =
public statement expressing displeasure with actions taken by a Director an=
d had asserted that he would remove the Director if the statute did not sta=
nd in the way. In those situations, the statutory provision would clearly c=
ause harm.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the present case, the situati=
on is less clear-cut, but the shareholders nevertheless claim that the unco=
nstitutional removal provision inflicted harm. Were it not for that provisi=
on, they suggest, the President might have replaced one of the confirmed Di=
rectors who supervised the implementation of the third amendment, or a conf=
irmed Director might=C2=A0 have altered his behavior in a way that would ha=
ve benefited the shareholders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The federal =
parties dispute the possibility that the unconstitutional removal restricti=
on caused any such harm. They argue that, irrespective of the President=E2=
=80=99s power to remove the FHFA Director, he =E2=80=9Cretained the power t=
o supervise the [Third] Amendment=E2=80=99s adoption . . . because FHFA=E2=
=80=99s counterparty to the Amendment was Treasury=E2=80=94an executive dep=
artment led by a Secretary subject to removal at will by the President.=E2=
=80=9D The parties=E2=80=99 arguments should be resolved in the first insta=
nce by the lower courts.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah =
the shareholders are not gonna win that one (by proving that a president wa=
nted to fire an FHFA director but didn=E2=80=99t?). The Supreme Court also =
rejected=C2=A0another, less interesting statutory argument against the thir=
d amendment. Fannie and Freddie may one day be back in shareholder hands, a=
nd the existing shareholders may get some value out of that, but it=E2=80=
=99s not going to be from these lawsuits. =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjMvZmFubmllLWZyZWRkaWUtaW52ZXN0b3JzL=
WdldC1taXhlZC1ydWxpbmctZnJvbS1zdXByZW1lLWNvdXJ0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30=
70ff6b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> C=
ommon shares of Fannie Mae slumped</a> as much as 42% and those of Freddie =
Mac plunged 44%, both posting their steepest intraday declines since Octobe=
r 2014.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quo=
t;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; fo=
nt-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margi=
n: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">Compliance</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>I don=E2=80=99t know, honestly, this is kind of a good policy for a broker=
age to have:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Employees are also=
 strictly prohibited from initiating contact with any Regulator without pri=
or approval from the Legal or Compliance Department. This prohibition appli=
es to any subject matter that might be discussed with a Regulator, includin=
g an individual=E2=80=99s registration status with FINRA. Any employee that=
 violates this policy may be subject to disciplinary action by the Firm.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like, if you have a bunch of emp=
loyees, and they are working on a bunch of creative trade ideas, you don=E2=
=80=99t want one of them to just pick up the phone and call the Securities =
and Exchange Commission and say =E2=80=9Chey I have an idea, is this legal?=
=E2=80=9D You want them to run their ideas by compliance and legal first, a=
nd make sure to work out the bugs and present the best possible version=C2=
=A0to the SEC. You want, as far as possible, to know what conversations you=
r firm is having with the SEC. Those conversations can be high-stakes for a=
 brokerage, so you want them to be centralized and coordinated by someone w=
ho knows what they=E2=80=99re doing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also o=
f course if some employee sees something at the firm that they think is ill=
egal, it would be=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>helpful, for the firm, if they we=
nt to the firm=E2=80=99s lawyers first. The lawyers=C2=A0might tell them =
=E2=80=9Cno no no that=E2=80=99s perfectly legal, here=E2=80=99s why.=E2=80=
=9D Or they might say =E2=80=9Coh you=E2=80=99re right that=E2=80=99s illeg=
al, we=E2=80=99d better tell the regulator,=E2=80=9D and then think of the =
best and most apologetic way to do that. Or =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean of course=
 you could imagine the lawyers taking another approach. (=E2=80=9CThat=E2=
=80=99s totally illegal but let=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>tell the r=
egulators, aren=E2=80=99t you in line for a raise this year?=E2=80=9D Etc.)=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So I get where the policy is coming from b=
ut it is also pretty illegal? The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci9=
0ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4yMUYtMTc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd6f6608e" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">SEC=E2=80=99s whistle-blo=
wer rules</a> say that =E2=80=9CNo person may take any action to impede an =
individual from communicating directly with the Commission staff about a po=
ssible securities law violation.=E2=80=9D If your corporate rules say =E2=
=80=9Cno one can call up the SEC for any reason,=E2=80=9D you are prohibiti=
ng your employees from whistle-blowing, and that=E2=80=99s not allowed.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Guggenheim Securities LLC =E2=80=94=C2=A0wh=
ich had this policy =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/24240248.258390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2=
FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzQtOTIyMzcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB838a303d" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">settled with the S=
EC today</a>, promising not to do it again and agreeing to pay $208,912. Oo=
ps! What one wants is a policy like =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t go cowboying aro=
und talking to regulators without telling compliance, but of course if you =
see anything illegal feel free to go to the regulators, that is your right =
as an American and we would never dream of stopping you, though it would be=
 a nice favor to us if you told us first.=E2=80=9D But it=E2=80=99s a littl=
e hard to convey that in writing.</p>
